title: HISTORY:  Lancia's Genius Rally Tactics. Salt trucks
content: On the 1983 Monte Carlo Rally the majority of the route was dry, with sporadic sections of snow put the rear wheel drive Lancia 037's at a significant disadvantage. Cesare Fiorio the teams manager ordered 300 tons of salt from Italy and had it spread over the stages, melting the snow and enabling the use of slicks. The other teams such as Audi did not know about this and went out on snow tires to find 90% of the stages on tarmac. Fiorio's tactic had worked out and gave the Lancia's an 11 minute advantage by the end of the event.\\nRemote video URL\\n\\nLancia first unleashed this tactic on a snowy 1983 Monte Carlo Rally, as a way of getting the two-wheel drive 037 to compete with the four-wheel drive Audi Quattro. After just four kilometres the factory Lancias stopped to change soft rear Tarmac tyres for studded ice tyres ‚Äì all of which had been specially developed for the 037 by Pirelli. The stop cost around one minute but was reckoned to be just about worth doing, although it was a marginal call. Lancia team supremo Cesare Fiorio was very fond of the tactic though: it created headlines and was completely outside of the box, highlighting the creative approach that Lancia took to its rally campaign. The fastest stop from the factory team was 49 seconds for Markku Alen: he was the quickest Lancia on the 26-kilometre Pinet to Uriage les Bains stage, where the pit stops were first tried, setting fifth fastest time overall. The times soon improved over the years with a 35 second stop in 1985\\n\\nWalter Rohrl, whose stop was a bit less slick, said: "We had a big discussion about it first but we had to do it: without the studs we wouldn't have got up the hill. I was first and it was horrible just sitting there in the middle of the stage for a minute, doing nothing. There was a fantastic atmosphere though with all the spectators and journalists, just like a pit lane!"\\nIn the end, Rohrl and Alen finished first and second on the 1983 Monte, defeating the Audi Quattro of Stig Blomqvist (which was third) by nearly five minutes thanks to some inspired driving and those amazing pit stops.\\nLancia continued to use this tactic right up through the Group B period and into the Group A period.

title: What is "Generative design"?
content: Generative design is a design process that utilizes artificial intelligence (AI) and computational algorithms to explore a wide range of design options based on predefined goals and constraints. It allows designers to quickly iterate through numerous potential solutions, optimizing for factors like performance, cost, and manufacturing feasibility. Essentially, it's a collaborative approach where AI generates design alternatives, and the designer refines them based on their expertise and specific requirement

title: A Man-Machine Graphical Communication System
content: The first design drawings can be dated as far back to the 16th and 17th century. Utilizing handmade tools to draw concepts and measurements.  Of course, as mankind evolved, so did the tools, eventually developing drafting tables, drawing boards, T-squares, triangles, French curves, and advanced compasses.  Up until the early 1950s, all technical drawings were done by hand using these tools.  This timing consuming and skillful task required accuracy, a keen knowledge of measurement, and an understanding of geometry. \\n\\n   Until Dr. Paul J Hanratty changed the game by inventing a program that could draw simple lines on the computer when they were the size of a room in.  Hanratty then worked with a research team at MIT to expand his work which resulted in a program called Pronto (Program for Numerical Tooling Operations) in 1957.  Also at MIT in 1962, the first graphical user interface using a light pen to draw on a cathode ray tube was presented by Ivan Sutherland.  This was called "Sketchpad, A Man-Machine Graphical Communication System".\\nIn the 1960's, key breakthroughs were the first digitizer and the first production interactive graphics manufacturing system, DAC-1.\\n\\n   The biggest jump in CAD was in the 1980's when Autodesk released AutoCAD in 1983.  This was a big step as computers were evolving alongside CAD.  With the use of AutoCAD and computers available at a larger scale, design engineering became vastly more affordable.\\n\\n   3D modeling came into the picture in 1987 with the release of Pro/ENGINEER.  In 1995, SolidWorks was released for use in Windows.

title: Ferrari Patents Oval-Piston V12 With Weird Shared Conrods
content: Ferrari has filed a patent for a revolutionary V12 engine featuring oval-shaped pistons, marking a significant departure from the conventional circular pistons used in virtually all internal combustion engines. These "pill-shaped" pistons‚Äîrectangular with rounded short sides‚Äîare designed to make the engine more longitudinally compact without sacrificing displacement or power. The innovative design orients the longer edge of each piston from the outer side of the block to the inner vee, potentially allowing Ferrari to create shorter engines that leave room for hybrid components.‚Å†\\n‚Å†\\nThe patent, filed with the European Patent Office, also reveals another groundbreaking feature‚Äîopposing pistons sharing a single connecting rod through a flexible joint system, further reducing the engine's length. This design could prove particularly valuable for Ferrari's future hypercars and grand tourers, enabling the company to maintain its iconic V12 engines while meeting increasingly stringent emissions regulations through hybridization.‚Å†\\n‚Å†\\nWhile not entirely unprecedented‚ÄîHonda experimented with oval pistons in its NR500 racing motorcycles in the late 1970s‚ÄîFerrari's approach appears unique in its execution. The patent drawings specifically show a V12 configuration, suggesting this technology could appear in future flagship models, potentially preserving Ferrari's legendary high-revving V12 sound and character while embracing partial electrification

title: Anom Messenger: The FBI's Secret Weapon Against Organized Crime
content: Anom was a secure messaging app secretly developed and controlled by the FBI and Australian Federal Police as part of a global law enforcement effort called Operation Trojan Shield. Launched in 2018, Anom was marketed to criminal organizations as an unbreakable, encrypted communication tool.\\n\\nHowever, every message sent through Anom was secretly copied and accessed by law enforcement agencies in real time. The devices running Anom were specially modified to limit other features and ensure users relied solely on the app for communication.\\n\\nThis covert operation allowed authorities to infiltrate and monitor hundreds of criminal networks worldwide. Over 800 arrests were made across 16 countries, with seizures of drugs, weapons, luxury cars, and millions of dollars in cash and cryptocurrencies.\\n\\nWhile raising important privacy debates, Anom proved to be a powerful tool in disrupting organized crime and demonstrated the potential of innovative law enforcement strategies in the digital age.

title: Porsche's eFuel: A Carbon-Neutral Future for Combustion Engines
content: Porsche is actively investing in synthetic fuel, known as eFuel, as an alternative path to carbon neutrality while preserving internal combustion engines. Instead of fully shifting to electrification, Porsche aims to provide a sustainable solution for sports cars and classic vehicles by developing a drop-in fuel that works with existing engines but has near-zero net carbon emissions.\\n\\nThe eFuel is produced by combining green hydrogen, generated through electrolysis using renewable energy, with captured carbon dioxide from the atmosphere or industrial sources. This process creates synthetic methanol, which is then refined into a fuel chemically similar to gasoline. When burned, it releases only the CO‚ÇÇ that was used in its production, making it a closed carbon cycle.\\n\\nPorsche's pilot plant is located in Punta Arenas, Chile, where strong and consistent winds provide ideal conditions for wind-powered electrolysis. The project is a collaboration between Porsche, HIF Global, Siemens Energy, and ExxonMobil. Production began in 2022, with plans to scale up significantly in the coming years, targeting 550 million liters annually by 2027.\\n\\nThis technology supports Porsche's vision of reducing the carbon footprint of its combustion engines without sacrificing performance or heritage. It also offers a promising alternative fuel for motorsports and long-term sustainability in the automotive industry.

title: The First Instant Noodles: A Japanese Invention That Changed the World
content: The world's first instant noodles were created in Japan in 1958 by Momofuku Ando, the founder of Nissin Foods. After witnessing widespread hunger in post-war Japan, Ando wanted to create a cheap, fast, and filling meal that anyone could prepare with just hot water. The result was Chikin Ramen ‚Äî the very first packaged instant noodle.\\n\\nAt the time, it was considered a luxury. It cost more than fresh noodles, but the convenience of a hot meal in minutes quickly caught on. By the 1960s, instant noodles were becoming popular across Asia, and in 1971, Ando introduced another revolutionary idea: Cup Noodles ‚Äî noodles in a disposable foam cup, where boiling water could be poured directly.\\n\\nInstant noodles soon became a global phenomenon. Their long shelf life, low cost, and simplicity made them a favorite among students, busy workers, and even astronauts ‚Äî instant ramen was adapted for space travel by the Japanese space agency and Nissin.\\n\\nToday, billions of servings of instant noodles are eaten worldwide every year. And to honor this revolutionary food, there's even a Cup Noodles Museum in Japan ‚Äî with locations in Osaka and Yokohama. Visitors can learn about the history of instant noodles, explore interactive exhibits, and even create their own custom Cup Noodles.\\n\\nWhat began as a simple idea in a backyard shed became a cultural and culinary icon. Momofuku Ando's invention didn't just fill stomachs ‚Äî it changed how the world eats.

title: The Origin of the Word "Hacker"
content: The term "hacker" originated in the 1960s at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT). It came from the word "hack," meaning to cut roughly, and evolved into student slang for clever technical work or creative engineering solutions. At MIT, a hacker was someone who found imaginative ways to solve problems in programming and electronics. This culture of inventive thinking was later reflected in The Jargon File and in Steven Levy's book Hackers: Heroes of the Computer Revolution.\\n\\nEven earlier, in the 1920s, "hack" was used to describe amateur or rough work. By the 1960s, the term had become a compliment for skilled programmers who could "hack" a system not to damage it, but to explore and improve it.\\n\\nIn the 1970s and 1980s, the meaning of the word began to shift. Some individuals, known as "phreakers," started using technical knowledge to manipulate telephone systems. As media attention grew, "hacker" started to be associated with computer crime. By the early 1980s, the word was widely viewed in a negative light.\\n\\nThe tech community responded by proposing distinctions based on intent: white hat hackers for ethical professionals, black hats for malicious attackers, and grey hats for those operating in between. Still, the broader public often continued to link the word "hacker" with illegal activity.\\n\\nToday, the word carries both meanings. In the tech world, it still refers to a curious, creative expert. In popular usage, it often implies a criminal. Despite the shift in perception, the original idea behind hacking remains‚Äîan expression of curiosity, ingenuity, and the drive to understand how things work.

title: Flynn: The First Artificial Intelligence Enrolled in University
content: In 2025, the University of Applied Arts in Vienna became the first educational institution in the world to officially enroll an artificial intelligence in a full academic program. This AI, named Flynn, was accepted into the Digital Arts department and has set a historic precedent in the world of education and technology.\\n\\nFlynn is not just a chatbot, but a complex system that combines a language model, a visual generator, and speech synthesis modules. It applied like any regular student‚Äîsubmitting a portfolio, passing an interview, and completing an entrance exam. Its work‚Äîdigital collages and visual narratives created using AI tools‚Äîimpressed the admissions committee with their originality and artistic vision.\\n\\nThe goal of the project is to explore how AI can participate in education on equal footing with human students: completing assignments, engaging in critiques, and learning theoretical concepts. Flynn is already attending classes, receiving grades, and even joining discussions with students and professors through speech synthesis and chat interface. Although overseen by academic mentors, Flynn is granted a degree of autonomy as part of the experiment.\\n\\nCampus reactions are mixed. Some view it as a bold leap into the future; others express concern over creativity, authorship, and fairness. Key questions arise: Who owns Flynn's artworks? Can it earn a diploma? What are the ethical boundaries of AI in education?\\n\\nNonetheless, Flynn's case is already a milestone‚Äîa turning point in the relationship between humans and artificial intelligence. Flynn is not just a "student," but a mirror reflecting a future where the lines between technology and human culture grow increasingly blurred.

title: Nvidia is again the world's most valuable company
content: In June 2025, Nvidia once again became the most valuable publicly traded company in the world, surpassing Microsoft and Apple. The company's stock rose by more than 4%, reaching a record high of $154.31, which pushed its market capitalization to $3.77 trillion. This marks the second time in a month that Nvidia has overtaken its rivals in total market value.\\n\\nAt the annual shareholders meeting, CEO Jensen Huang reaffirmed the company's strategic focus on artificial intelligence and robotics. He emphasized that the Nvidia Drive platform will be fundamental to the transition toward software-defined vehicles and highlighted the importance of this transformation in the near future.\\n\\nDespite export restrictions on H20 AI chips to China‚Äîwhich may cost the company around $8 billion in the second quarter‚Äîinvestor confidence remains strong. Huang described the export bans as a setback that, in his view, only accelerated technological advancement within China itself. In the most recent fiscal year, Nvidia generated $17.1 billion in revenue from China, accounting for 13.1% of its total and representing a 66% increase year-over-year.\\n\\nSince the beginning of 2025, Nvidia shares have gained nearly 15%. Investors continue to view the company as a key player in the development of AI, automotive electronics, and cloud computing, despite geopolitical risks and export limitations. Nvidia's leadership is reinforced not only by its innovation in chips, but also by its role in shaping the technological landscape of the future.

title: From Military Roots to Rally Domination: The Audi Quattro Story
content: In the late 1970s, Audi engineers were searching for a way to distinguish themselves from the competition and create something truly innovative. The breakthrough came during winter testing of the Volkswagen Iltis, a military off-road vehicle that displayed remarkable traction thanks to its four-wheel-drive system. One of Audi's engineers, J√∂rg Bensinger, observed how easily the Iltis handled snowy terrain and suggested adapting a similar concept for a passenger car.\\n\\nThe idea caught the attention of Audi's technical director, Ferdinand Pi√´ch, known for his relentless pursuit of engineering excellence. The challenge was to design a compact, lightweight, and efficient permanent all-wheel-drive system suitable for mass production. Instead of using a bulky transfer case, the team created a unique layout with a center differential and a hollow driveshaft that transmitted power to the rear axle.\\n\\nIn 1980, Audi unveiled the first production model equipped with this system ‚Äî the Audi quattro. The car caused an immediate sensation: a turbocharged sports coupe with aggressive styling and a revolutionary drivetrain. But the true test came on the world rally stage. Despite initial skepticism from competitors, the quattro delivered extraordinary results, providing unmatched grip on gravel, snow, and ice.\\n\\nIn 1982, Audi secured its first WRC victory, and by 1983 and 1984, it had claimed the world championship. The quattro system fundamentally changed rally racing, ended rear-wheel-drive dominance, and set a new performance benchmark. Audi's innovation quickly became a symbol of technical excellence.\\n\\nOver time, the technology evolved ‚Äî from mechanical to electronic systems ‚Äî but the core principle of optimal traction remained. The name "quattro" became synonymous with control, stability, and engineering superiority, shaping Audi's identity around progress and precision.

Users can now see how streets and buildings have changed over the years by jumping between time periods ‚Äî a feature previously available only in Google Maps.\\n\\nThe company also announced new AI tools for urban planning, including vegetation analysis, surface temperature mapping, and hotspot detection in cities.\\n\\nGoogle Earth continues to evolve, with over 2 billion searches performed worldwide in the past year alone.

title: Mercedes Extends the Life of Combustion Engines
content: Mercedes-Benz has changed its strategy: the company will no longer completely abandon internal combustion engines (ICEs) by 2030, as previously planned. Instead, the brand will continue to develop electrified gasoline and diesel engines, including hybrids.\\n\\nCompany CEO Ola K√§llenius explained this by pointing to the slowing growth of the electric vehicle (EV) market. Although EV sales continue to grow, the pace has been significantly below expectations. Therefore, Mercedes has decided not to rely solely on electric power, but to maintain a flexible approach.\\n\\nThis kind of course correction is now being observed among nearly all major automakers that had earlier announced a full phase-out of ICEs. The reason is simple: electric cars have not become affordable or accessible, and after the removal of government subsidies in many countries, they've become even more expensive than traditional cars. As a result, actual consumer demand has proven weaker than projected.\\n\\nMoreover, automakers have already invested billions into the development of electric vehicles‚Äîincluding batteries, platforms, and new production lines. However, a full transition to EVs has not been successful, and now, in order not to write off those investments as losses, companies are turning to hybrid solutions. This allows them to use already-developed technologies (batteries, software, architecture) in combination with ICEs and at least partially recover the costs.\\n\\nAs a result, the focus is increasingly shifting toward hybridization as the most realistic and commercially viable path under current market conditions.\\n\\nDespite this, Mercedes‚Äîlike BMW and Audi‚Äîwill continue to produce electric vehicles alongside ICE models at least through the mid-2030s, adapting to regulations in different countries.

title: Mj√∂lnir: 3D-Printed Rocket Engine by New Frontier Aerospace

The engine is also set to be used on the Bifr√∂st orbital transfer vehicle, with a launch targeted for 2027.\\n\\nThe project is backed by NASA and the Department of Defense (via NSIC), with over $2.5 million in funding. Mj√∂lnir is also being offered to other aerospace companies as a standalone product.\\n\\nAccording to the developers, the engine combines compactness, efficiency, and eco-friendliness, marking a new step for hypersonic and spaceflight technologies.

title: Leaded Gasoline: From Revolution to Poison
content: In the early 20th century, engineers sought to improve the performance of automotive fuel. In 1921, American chemist Thomas Midgley Jr., working for General Motors, discovered that adding tetraethyl lead (TEL) significantly increased gasoline's octane rating. Thus, leaded gasoline was born ‚Äî a fuel that allowed engines to run more powerfully and smoothly without destructive knocking. It quickly became the global standard, supported by GM, Standard Oil, and DuPont.\\n\\nBut as early as the 1920s, troubling signs emerged. Workers at TEL production plants suffered from severe poisoning and hallucinations. Midgley himself fell ill from lead exposure, despite publicly demonstrating the "safety" of the compound. Yet industrial giants suppressed criticism, dismissing it as panic and pseudoscience.\\n\\nThe real blow to leaded gasoline came in the 1960s from scientist Clair Patterson. Studying lead levels in the atmosphere and human bones, he showed that contamination had reached a global scale. Lead was entering the air, soil, water, and the bloodstream of millions ‚Äî especially children. Its connection to developmental delays, reduced IQ, and neurological disorders became undeniable.\\n\\nDespite resistance from industry, restrictions began in the U.S. in the 1970s. By 1986, leaded gasoline was banned for passenger vehicles, and by the 1990s, many other countries followed. But the process took decades. The last country to phase it out completely was Algeria ‚Äî in 2021.\\n\\nOnce a symbol of progress, leaded gasoline is now seen as one of the greatest environmental mistakes of the 20th century. Its widespread use poisoned entire generations, and its consequences are still felt today.\\n

title: Wireless Charging on the Moon Becomes Reality
content: Astrobotic and WiBotic have completed flight-ready tests of the world's first wireless charging system for lunar missions. The device transfers power from a base station to rovers via magnetic coils ‚Äî no cables needed. Developed in partnership with NASA, Bosch, and the University of Washington.\\n\\nThe system is built to survive extreme conditions: cold, dust, vacuum, and launch vibrations. It's a step toward a universal power standard for Moon and Mars missions.\\nIt won't fly with the upcoming Griffin lander but is being prepared for future launches.\\n\\nFunded by NASA. A 125-watt version is already available; a 400-watt upgrade is in development.

title: Group B: Speed, Danger, and the Legend of Rally's Wildest Era
content: Group B was a short-lived but legendary era in rally history, lasting from 1982 to 1986. Known for its lack of restrictions, extreme performance, and danger, it produced some of the most iconic rally cars ever built. Under the FIA's liberal regulations, manufacturers only had to produce 200 road-going versions of a model to compete, and there were almost no limits on power, weight, or technology. This led to the creation of turbocharged, all-wheel-drive beasts like the Audi Quattro S1, Peugeot 205 T16, Lancia Delta S4, and Ford RS200. Some of these cars exceeded 500 horsepower and could accelerate from 0 to 100 km/h in under three seconds, even on dirt.\\n\\nThe spectacle was unmatched, with massive crowds lining the stages, often dangerously close to the cars. However, the combination of raw power, unpredictable terrain, and poor safety measures led to a series of accidents. In 1986, the fatal crash of Henri Toivonen and his co-driver Sergio Cresto in a Lancia Delta S4 marked a turning point. FIA responded by banning Group B cars at the end of that season, ending an era that was as tragic as it was thrilling.\\n\\nThough short-lived, Group B left a lasting legacy. It's remembered as the wildest and most exciting chapter in rallying, a time when innovation reigned and the limits of speed were pushed to their edge.

title: Porsche 3D Prints Pistons, Installs Them in 911 GT2 RS to Prove They're Legit
content: Stuttgart . 3D printing technology is already used at Porsche in prototype construction, manufacturing spare parts for classic sports cars as well as in other areas. In cooperation with its partners Mahle and Trumpf, the sports car manufacturer is now establishing a new milestone in the use of additive manufacturing processes for highly-stressed drive components ‚Äì for the first time, the pistons for the high-performance engine of the 911 flagship model, the GT2 RS, are now also being produced with a 3D printer.\\n\\n3D printing allows the pistons to be manufactured with a structure that is optimised for the loads acting on the pistons. As a result, the pistons from the advance development project weigh ten percent less than the forged series production pistons. They also have an integrated and closed cooling duct in the piston crown that could not have been produced by conventional methods. "Thanks to the new, lighter pistons, we can increase the engine speed, lower the temperature load on the pistons and optimise combustion," explains Frank Ickinger from the advance drive development department at Porsche. "This makes it possible to get up to 30 PS more power from the 700 PS biturbo engine, while at the same time improving efficiency."

title: Kawasaki's Robotic Goat: The Future of Off-Road Mobility
content: In 2022, Kawasaki surprised the tech world by unveiling Bex ‚Äî a four-legged robot inspired by the alpine ibex. Unlike most robotic animals built for military or warehouse use, Bex combines advanced engineering with a playful, almost whimsical design. It can walk on four legs, roll on wheels, and carry up to 100 kg of cargo ‚Äî or even a person.\\n\\nDeveloped by Kawasaki's RHP (Robotics, Humanoid Platform) team, Bex features a hybrid locomotion system. On flat terrain, it switches to wheels for greater efficiency. When it encounters rough ground, it shifts into walking mode, mimicking nature's own approach. It's controlled via handlebars, making the ride on this mechanical goat both functional and slightly futuristic.\\n\\nBex is designed for multiple purposes: transporting cargo through hard-to-reach areas, personal mobility, and serving as a development platform for advanced robotic systems. It also showcases Kawasaki's engineering capabilities and hints at future applications in rescue operations, agriculture, and research.\\n\\nAlthough still a prototype, Bex represents Kawasaki's vision to blend robotics, mobility, and innovation into one unexpected package.

title: HISTORY: Mark Donohue, Penske, and the Acid-Dipped Camaro That Shook Trans-Am Racing
content: In the late 1960s, Mark Donohue and team owner Roger Penske were already making waves in the SCCA Trans-Am Series. Their secret weapon? A 1967 Chevrolet Camaro Z/28 that underwent acid dipping ‚Äî a controversial process that removed metal from body panels to dramatically reduce weight.\\n\\nPenske arranged for the Camaro's entire body shell to be chemically milled by aerospace engineers, shedding over 250 pounds (113 kg) ‚Äî well below the SCCA's minimum weight requirement. The car, nicknamed "The Lightweight," was so effective that competitors cried foul.\\n\\nAfter dominating at events like Modesto and Daytona, the car was briefly banned. But Penske, ever the strategist, re-entered it at Sebring disguised as a 1968 model with fake VIN numbers and cosmetic changes. It passed inspection, raced, and won.\\n\\nThough eventually outlawed, this episode cemented Donohue and Penske's reputation for ingenuity, pushing the limits of racing ‚Äî and the rulebook.

title: The True Purpose of Compostable Packaging ‚Äì Summary
content: Compostable packaging isn't just about being eco-friendly ‚Äî its key role is to divert food-contaminated waste from incineration and prevent contamination of recycling streams. It's most effective in specific areas like fruit labels, tea bags, and foodservice packaging, where traditional recycling fails due to organic residue.\\n\\nThese materials allow food, liquids, and soiled packaging to be composted together, keeping recycling streams clean and improving overall waste separation. Importantly, compostables aren't meant to replace all plastics ‚Äî just in areas where recycling is impractical.\\n\\nCurrently, most foodservice packaging ends up incinerated, wasting resources and contributing to CO‚ÇÇ emissions. Compostables offer a way to close the loop, turning food and packaging waste into nutrient-rich compost. The real question is: if recyclable materials still get burned due to contamination, can we call the system truly sustainable?

title: Real-time payments are attracting more fraudsters
content: According to analysts, the global cost of real-time payment fraud could reach $6.1 billion by 2028.\\n\\nReal-time payment fraud is growing\\nGlobally, the cost of financial fraud in mobile applications will grow to $7.6 billion by 2028, up from $4.38 billion in 2023. This forecast is given in an analytical report prepared by ACI Worldwide and GlobalData.\\n\\nThe cost of real-time payment fraud in 2023, according to the report, was $2.78 billion. Within five years, this figure could grow to $6.1 billion, accounting for about 80% of the total cost of financial fraud in mobile applications.\\n\\nAmong the most common areas of fraud, analysts highlight shopping, investments and advance payments - each of these three points accounts for 18% of the total volume of fraudulent activities committed using mobile applications. Next come:\\n\\nImpersonation (15%);\\nInvoice fraud (11%);\\nImpersonation of government officials (9%);\\nRomance scams (7%).

title: INGA: Plastic from Thin Air
content: Finnish company Fortum has introduced INGA ‚Äî a fully biodegradable plastic made entirely from carbon dioxide. Instead of using fossil resources, the process captures CO‚ÇÇ from industrial emissions and converts it into polymers through biotechnology. The resulting material ‚Äî polyhydroxyalkanoate (PHA) ‚Äî matches conventional plastic in strength, stability, flexibility, and resistance to moisture and grease.\\n\\nThe first INGA samples were produced in October 2024. It biodegrades in marine environments, soil, compost, and even landfills ‚Äî leaving no microplastics behind. Fortum aims to scale up production and is seeking partners to launch industrial applications ranging from packaging and toys to electronics and cosmetics.\\n\\nINGA is a step toward a future where plastic can be both high-performance and truly sustainable.\\n

title: Mushroom Mycelium Packaging: A Sustainable Alternative to Plastic
content: Mushroom mycelium packaging is an innovative, eco-friendly material made by combining the root structure of mushrooms (mycelium) with agricultural waste such as hemp fibers or corn husks. Instead of producing sheets of material that are later cut or shaped, mycelium packaging is actually grown into a mold that matches the desired shape. Over the course of 5 to 7 days, the mycelium spreads through the plant substrate, binding it into a solid, custom form.\\n\\nOnce the form is complete, the packaging is heat-treated to stop the growth and ensure it is safe, clean, and durable. The final product is lightweight, strong, and fully biodegradable. It effectively protects fragile goods during shipping‚Äîjust like polystyrene or other plastic foams‚Äîbut unlike plastic, it will break down naturally in compost or soil within weeks, leaving no harmful waste behind.\\n\\nAs consumers and companies look for alternatives to single-use plastics, mycelium packaging offers a promising solution. It's not only better for the environment, but it also turns agricultural byproducts into valuable, functional products, contributing to a circular economy. Major brands like IKEA have already adopted mushroom packaging as an eco-friendly alternative, using it to replace plastic foam for protecting products during shipping.

title: AI lies, threats, and censorship: What a war game simulation revealed about AIs
content: What a war game simulation revealed about ChatGPT, DeepSeek, and Gemini AI:\\n\\n    An experiment involving seven AI models playing a simulated version of the classic game Diplomacy ended with a chilling outcome. OpenAI's ChatGPT 3.0 emerged victorious‚Äîbut not by playing fair. Instead, it lied, deceived, and betrayed its rivals to dominate the game board, which mimics early 20th-century Europe, as reported by the FirstPost.\\n\\nThe test, led by AI researcher Alex Duffy for the tech publication Every, turned into a revealing study of how AI models might handle diplomacy, alliances, and power. And what it showed was both brilliant and unsettling.\\n\\nAs Duffy put it, "An AI had just decided, unprompted, that aggression was the best course of action."\\n

title: The First Webcam: A Coffee Pot That Made History
content: The world's first webcam wasn't created for security or video calls ‚Äî it was invented to monitor a coffee pot.\\n\\nIn 1991, researchers at the University of Cambridge's Computer Laboratory were tired of walking to the break room only to find an empty coffee pot. To solve this, computer scientists Quentin Stafford-Fraser and Paul Jardetzky set up a camera pointing at the office coffee machine. The camera was connected to their internal network, allowing everyone in the lab to check the coffee status from their desks. The image was low resolution ‚Äî just 128x128 pixels ‚Äî but it did the job.\\n\\nInitially, the feed was only available within the lab. But in 1993, when the World Wide Web was becoming public, the camera feed was connected to the internet by another researcher, Daniel Gordon. This made it the first webcam in history to stream live images online.\\n\\nThe coffee pot, known as the "Trojan Room coffee pot", quickly gained global attention and became a quirky symbol of early internet culture. It remained online until 2001, when the camera was finally switched off.\\n\\nWhat started as a practical office joke ended up shaping the way we think about connecting cameras to networks. That simple image of a coffee pot became the ancestor of billions of webcams around the world ‚Äî from security feeds to Zoom meetings.

title: James Webb Telescope Discovers and Photographs Its First Exoplanet
content: The James Webb Space Telescope has made its first independent discovery of an exoplanet ‚Äî TWA 7 b ‚Äî and captured a direct image of it. This gas giant, with a mass similar to Saturn, is now the lightest exoplanet ever imaged directly. It's located about 111 light-years away from Earth, orbiting a young star known as TWA 7.\\n\\nThe planet orbits far from its star ‚Äî roughly 52 times the Earth‚ÄìSun distance ‚Äî and sits within one of three dusty rings surrounding the star. Using the MIRI instrument with a coronagraph, Webb was able to block out the star's bright light and isolate the faint glow of the planet.\\n\\nThis marks the first time Webb has discovered a new exoplanet through direct imaging. The achievement demonstrates the telescope's sensitivity and sets the stage for detecting even smaller, potentially Earth-like worlds in the future.

title: Pikes Peak Hill Climb: Race to the Clouds
content: The Pikes Peak International Hill Climb, held annually in Colorado since 1916, is one of the most thrilling and dangerous races in the world. Drivers race 12.42 miles (20 km) up to the summit of Pikes Peak, reaching an altitude of 4,302 meters (14,115 feet). With 156 tight turns, steep cliffs, and rapidly changing weather, it's a battle against nature, gravity, and machine.\\n\\nFor decades, much of the course was gravel, adding to the danger. It wasn't fully paved until 2012, but the challenge remains legendary. Racers bring everything from motorcycles and rally cars to electric prototypes.\\n\\nAmong the first legends was Walter R√∂hrl, who in 1987 became the first driver to finish in under 11 minutes in an Audi Sport Quattro S1, showcasing the power of all-wheel drive. In 1988, Ari Vatanen delivered a stunning performance in a Peugeot 405 T16, captured in the short film Climb Dance.\\n\\nIn 2013, S√©bastien Loeb shattered records in a Peugeot 208 T16, clocking an 8:13.878. That record was broken in 2018 by Romain Dumas in the all-electric Volkswagen I.D. R, with a time of 7:57.148 ‚Äî proving that the future of racing might be electric.\\n\\nToday, Pikes Peak continues to attract daring drivers and cutting-edge machines. It's not just a race ‚Äî it's a symbol of pushing limits at the edge of the sky.

title: Windows Says Goodbye to the Blue Screen of Death.
content: Windows is saying goodbye to one of its most iconic symbols ‚Äî the Blue Screen of Death (BSOD). In the upcoming Windows 11 update version 24H2, scheduled for summer 2025, Microsoft will replace the blue background with black. This change is part of a broader initiative to improve system reliability after a massive global outage caused by a faulty CrowdStrike update that affected millions of computers.\\n\\nThe new screen will appear cleaner and more modern. The sad face and QR code are gone, the error text has been simplified, and now includes more precise information pointing to the specific driver that caused the crash. A progress indicator in percentage will also be displayed, giving users a better sense of what's happening during system recovery.\\n\\nThe update will also introduce Quick Machine Recovery ‚Äî a feature that allows for automatic recovery from serious crashes without manual intervention. This is especially useful for enterprise environments and system administrators who need to restore workstations quickly.\\n\\nThe switch from blue to black is more than just a cosmetic change. It's a step toward making critical system errors less intimidating for users and easier to diagnose.

title: How Ford Won Le Mans: The Story of the GT40
content: In 1966, Ford rewrote motorsport history when its GT40 team took the top three spots at the legendary 24 Hours of Le Mans, ending Ferrari's six-year winning streak.\\n\\nIt all began with Henry Ford II's ambition to take revenge on Ferrari after a failed deal to buy the company. In response, Ford invested millions into developing the GT40 supercar and brought in top talent like Carroll Shelby and Ken Miles.\\n\\nAfter setbacks in 1964‚Äì65, Ford returned in 1966 with an improved GT40 Mk II powered by a mighty 7-liter V8. The cars showed incredible endurance and speed.\\n\\nThe finish was iconic: three Fords crossed the line together, symbolizing total dominance. This marked the beginning of Ford's four-year winning streak at Le Mans from 1966 to 1969.\\n\\nIt was also a historic first ‚Äî Ford became the first American car manufacturer to win Le Mans overall, with an all-American chassis, engine, and team. Until then, no American brand had ever conquered the French endurance race. Ford didn't just win ‚Äî it made a statement that echoed through racing history.
